descriptionMd:
As [dead internet theory](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dead_Internet_theory) enters mainstream discourse—the belief that bots will eventually outnumber real people—[alive internet theory](https://news.spencer.place/p/alive-internet-theory) offers a counter-narrative: the internet will always be filled with real people: looking for each other, answering calls for help, and sharing laughs even in the midst of arguing.
&nbsp;
***alive internet theory*** is a séance with this living internet. Resurrecting tens of millions of digital artifacts from the [Internet Archive](https://archive.org/), visitors are immersed in a relentless barrage of human expression as they travel through the life of the web as we created it—every image, video, song, and text uploaded by a real person on the web.
&nbsp;
Showing undeniably human material in the whirlwind format designed for algorithms represents the paradox of the modern web. What separates us from machines? And ultimately, what makes us human?
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
I wrote more about [alive internet theory](https://news.spencer.place/p/alive-internet-theory) on my newsletter.

